Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation with a confirmation dialog**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` (hardware/gesture back) and hook into Shell's navigating event:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
            {
                bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                    "Unsaved Changes",
                    "Discard changes?",
                    "Discard", "Stay");
                if (leave)
                {
                    _hasUnsavedChanges = false;
                    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
                }
            });
            return true; // cancel the default navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }

    protected override void OnAppearing()
    {
        base.OnAppearing();
        Shell.Current.Navigating += OnShellNavigating;
    }

    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();
        Shell.Current.Navigating -= OnShellNavigating;
    }

    // Catches Shell-driven navigation (e.g. tab switches, URI nav)
    private async void OnShellNavigating(object sender, ShellNavigatingEventArgs e)
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges) return;

        var deferral = e.GetDeferral();

        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave)
            e.Cancel(); // stay on page

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button**

In your XAML, hide the default back button and add your own toolbar item:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{StaticResource CancelBack}">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <BackButtonBehavior x:Key="CancelBack"
                            IsVisible="True"
                            TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>
</ContentPage>
```

Or set it inline:

```xml
<Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                        Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
</Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
```

Then in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
public ICommand CancelCommand => new Command(async () =>
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes", "Discard changes?", "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!leave) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
});
```

**Key points:**
- `OnBackButtonPressed` → handles Android hardware/swipe back (return `true` to cancel).
- `Shell.Navigating` + `GetDeferral()` → intercepts all Shell navigation asynchronously.
- `BackButtonBehavior.TextOverride` → replaces the back arrow with "Cancel" text.
- When using `BackButtonBehavior.Command`, the default back navigation is replaced entirely — you must call `GoToAsync("..")` yourself.
